{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525327"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:15:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:15:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14077"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14077"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.27,0.17,0.31,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6743"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53638"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6743"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14077"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39099"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2880"},{"type":"tags","id":"4032"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14588"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43476"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53638"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about her peritoneal dialysis. She has been on peritoneal dialysis for end-stage kidney disease due to membranous nephropathy for the past two years. She reports feeling more bloated than usual and notes that her fluid removal on dialysis has decreased over the past week. Her bowels last opened three days ago. Her urine output has not decreased. She has no other symptoms. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes, hypertension, and hyperlipidaemia. Her medications include insulin, amlodipine, atorvastatin. In the past few days, she was commenced on erythropoietin. She has had no previous abdominal surgeries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 155/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft, distended and tympanic to percussion. Recent laboratory investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 550 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum urea: 28 mmol/L (2.5-6.7)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum potassium: 5.4 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her poor peritoneal dialysis efficacy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bowel obstruction","Catheter malfunction","Erythropoietin","Constipation","Peritonitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation strongly suggests that \u003Cstrong\u003Econstipation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause of her poor peritoneal dialysis efficacy. The patient reports feeling bloated, has decreased fluid removal, and admits to not having had a bowel movement in three days. Constipation can significantly impair peritoneal dialysis efficiency by reducing both fluid removal and solute clearance. This is due to the increased intra-abdominal pressure from constipation, which can reduce the surface area available for dialysis and impair fluid and solute transport across the peritoneal membrane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely as the patient does not report vomiting or abdominal pain, there is no history of previous abdominal surgeries, and the patient\u0027s abdomen is soft on examination. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatheter malfunction\u003C/strong\u003E can certainly lead to poor dialysis efficacy, but the patient\u0027s main complaint is bloating, and constipation should always be the first reversible cause addressed in patients on peritoneal dialysis with poor fluid removal, before assessing for more sinister causes. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythropoietin\u003C/strong\u003E is a medication used in patients with chronic kidney disease to address anaemia. It has no relation to the patient\u0027s symptoms or issues with dialysis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeritonitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a serious complication of peritoneal dialysis, but it typically presents with abdominal pain, cloudy dialysate, and often fever. While it can affect dialysis efficacy, the patient\u0027s presentation does not suggest an acute infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management would be to address the constipation, likely with laxatives, and to emphasise the importance of regular bowel movements for effective peritoneal dialysis. Regular assessment and management of bowel habits should be an integral part of care for peritoneal dialysis patients. Once the constipation is resolved, the dialysis efficacy should improve. If problems persist, further investigations into other potential causes may be warranted.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Constipation can significantly impair peritoneal dialysis efficiency by reducing fluid removal and solute clearance.","Aperients are the first-line treatment for constipation in peritoneal dialysis patients to improve dialysis efficacy.","Regular bowel habits assessment and management is crucial in peritoneal dialysis patients."],"references":["Reimann F, Tomlins M. Prescribing and peritoneal dialysis. Australian Prescriber. 2023 Jun 22;46(1):5\u20138. Available at: https://australianprescriber.tg.org.au/articles/prescribing-and-peritoneal-dialysis.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39099"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14077"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39099"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-23T16:12:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T16:13:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6743"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53638"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not suitable for a medical student","position":2,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,